#Text=William
#Text=Elderton ( ballad writer )
#Text=The true fourme and shape of a monsterous Chyld / Which was borne in Stony Stratforde , in North Hampton shire
#Text=Ballad sheet written by William Elderton .
#Text=Huntington Library .
#Text=William Elderton
#Text=( died 1592 ? ) was an actor , lawyer , and prolific English ballad -writer , well known in London literary circles .
#Text=Life
#Text=Elderon first appears as an actor playing the fourth son of the Lord of Misrule , played by George Ferrers , at the court of Edward VI during the 1552-1553 Christmas season . [ 1 ]
#Text=His son , also named William , was christened on 16 January 1548 as recorded in the parish register of St. Peter 's upon Cornhill , London .
#Text=His wife , Grace Clearton , was buried on 9 November 1553 , in the same church , and his servant , Steven Riche , on 8 December 8 of the same year . [ 2 ]
#Text=Works
#Text=An early dated ballad of Elderton is The Panges of Loue and louers fttes ( sic ) , 1559 .
#Text=Michael Drayton
#Text=, in his epistle to Henry Reynolds , writes —
#Text=I scornd your ballet then , though it were done And had for Finis William Elderton .
#Text=A lost book , entitled Eldertons Jestes with his mery Toyes , was licensed for publication in 1561-2 ( Arber , Transcript , i. 179 ) .
#Text=It provoked ' An Admonition to Elderton to leave the toyes by him begone , ' which was followed by ' Eldertons answere for his mery toyes . '
#Text=Both the ' Admonition ' and the ' Answer ' are also lost .
#Text=Among Elderton 's extant ballads are
#Text='
#Text=The true fourme and shape of a monstrous chyld which was borne at Stony Stratforde ... 1565 ' ;
#Text=' An Epytaphe upon the Death of the Right Reverent and learned Father in God , I. Iuell , ' 1571 ;
#Text=' A ballat intituled Northomberland Newes , ' &c . , n. d. ( licensed 1569 ) ;
#Text=' A new Yorkshyre song , ' &c . , 1584 , describing a match at archery , in twenty-two six-line stanzas .
#Text=Some verses of Elderton are printed before Claudius Hollyband ' s Arnalt and Lucenda , 1575 .
#Text=John Stow

#Text=in his ' Survey , ' ( chapter on ' Cheape Warde ' ) , quotes some verses on the images over the Guildhall Gate , composed ' about thirty yeares since by William Elderton , at that time an Atturney in the Sheriifes Courtes there .
#Text=' From ' A true reporte of the death and martyrdome of M. Campion , ' 1581 , it appears that he published some ' scurile balates ' on Edmund Campion ' s execution .
#Text=Elderton died in or before 1592 .

#Text=In that year Gabriel Harvey published his ' Foure Letters , ' in which he describes Elderton and Robert Greene as ' two notorious mates and the very ringleaders of the riming and scribbling crew ' .
#Text=He speaks in the same tract of ' Elderton 's ale-crammed nose .
#Text='
#Text=Thomas Nashe

#Text=, in ' Foure Letters Confuted , ' 1593 , upbraids Harvey for ' plucking Elderton out of the ashes of his ale , ' and says that there had been a ' monstrous emulation ' between Elderton and Harvey .
#Text=There are two jocular epitaphs on Elderton in William Camden ' s ' Remaines , ' 1605 , p.56 .

#Text=Some of his ballads were re-printed by John Payne Collier for the Percy Society ( ' Old Ballads from Early Printed Copies ' ) in 1840 ; others are included in ' Ancient Ballads and Broadsides ' ( Philobiblon Society ) , 1867 .
#Text=The opening lines of a ballad by Elderton are quoted in Much Ado about Nothing , v. 2 .
#Text=John Ward , in Journal of the American Musicological Society , 1957 , X , p.164 gives more detail of this song " The God of Love " , as sung by Benedick in Much Ado about Nothing .
